t531.text: What we ended up with was a close family who respect the rights of individuals. Four strong willed and independent children. A scorn for authority so that respect has to be earned not freely given. And the realisation that country or government is meaningless

t532.text: A State a library card became a treasured possession. Books were invaluable possessions that could be traded, not hoarded. Knowing how to keep that old Troopie going was an essential skill.

t533.text: We were happy to wash in rivers. Wash our clothes in a bucket with a plunger, how to gather water safely so we did not need to head back into town.

t534.text: Yes they were good times. Funny after 3 years the family hardly recognised us. OK I admit we looked a little feral, a bit hippyish. But clothes to us needed to be practical. If something did not have a practical purpose then it was useless to us.

t535.text: We went where we wanted, when we wanted. We knew of every free camp site across half of Australia. Our children grew up independent. They decided that school could wait if the surf was good. Catching fish for dinner was an important lesson in understanding nature

t536.text: From being a management consultant, I soon learnt cleaning toilets could pay the rent, gutting fish in a fish factory put food on our plates.

t537.text: No TV, only a fridge, primitive solar panels for power. Learnt water was precious. Could cook most things over an open fire. Kids controlled their learning. Worked when we had to

t538.text: 20 y.ago sold everything we owned, packed up 4 kids 7-12 left professional jobs and travelled in a camper trailer for nearly 3 years. We have never felt freer, less beholden and more alive. Taught us a lot about life and what is important.
